{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/00414211021/1949042201/0555.xml":{"full_text":"THE CURREHT ECONOMIC PICTURE\n(Editor's Note: Since Mr. Gaeth's\nbroadcast a couple of weeks back,\nunemployment the nation over has\nshown an increasing: trend. Recent\nnews reports indicate that upwards\nof 600,000 are unemployed in\nthe state of California alone and that\nalmost half of the nation's unem\nployed are concentrated in the three\nPacific coast states. Other reports\nindicate that the recession of 1949\nseems to be hitting pretty generally\nover the entire nation, and, unless\neffective steps are taken immediate\nly by the congress the nation may be\ninto a major depression before the\nyear is out.)\nBy ARTHUR GAETH\nUE-CIO Radio Commentator\nAre we on the verge of an econom\nic bust or can we go along with the\nPresident and agree that the situa\ntion is nothing to be alarmed about,\nthat it is the leveling-off we have\nbeen hoping for? These facts con\nfront us: Operations in the cotton\nend of the textile industry are off\nabout 20 per cent. There is a siz\nable amount of unemployment in the\nmill towns of the south. The rail\nroads have laid off over 100,000\nworkers. There are sizable lay-offs\nin the repair shops in every major\nsystem. Freight hauling is down at\nleast 10 percent. In ship building,\nonly 25,000 people are working on\nnew ship construction,\nwork is gone. Repair work is the\nmajor function of the maritime in\ndustry; and in January, 1949, Todd\nand Bethlehem laid off 20,000 work\ners from their repair yards.\nWith at least a 50-day stock of\ncoal above ground, with foreign trade\ncut in half and unseasonably warm\nweather here in the east, thousands\nof coal miners are working two and\nthree days a week. In New York,\na leading daily newspaper has lost\n125,000 in circulation; the New York\nDrydock\nStar went out of business; another\nnewspaper has been forced to cut\nexpenses $10,000 a week, is looking\nfor a half million dollar loan. All\nnewspapers are seeing their adver\ntising cut.\n1948 Model Cars Selling $300\nBelow List Price\nin the automobile industry, work\nis holding up pretty well, production\nis ahead of last year. Kaiser-Frazer\nhas laid off 6,000 workers. At pres\nent 15,000 of that company's em\nployees are out for three weeks be\ncause of re-tooling. Lincoln-Mer\ncury production has also been cut.\nIn the selling end of the automobile\nindustry, heavy trucks are not mov\ning with the exception of the cheaper\nmodels\u2014and none of them are very\ncheap today. You can get almost\nevery car on immediate delivery. In\nNew York, in some lines, 1948 mod\nels are selling $300 below list price.\nIt has been a long time since that\nhappened.\nIn the clothing industry, there is\nconsiderable under employment\npeople working a few days a week\nor skipping weeks. There is optim\nism there will soon be a pick up for\nthe fall line. That optimism doesn't\nprevail in the shoe industry where\nemployment is limted. In Massa\nchusetts, workers average 22 to 28\nhours a week. In New York, the\nlargest manufacturer of women's\nshoes went broke last month. Twen\nty per cent of the workers now earn\nless than 80 cents an hour. In the\nelectrical industry which makes ra\ndios, washing machines, stoves, r\u00e9\nfrig\u00e9ra t\u00f4rs, all kinds of appliances\nas well as motors and heavy equip\nment, about 16 per cent of the work\ners employed at the 1948 peak have\nbeen laid off in 433 plants surveyed.\nNew Jobs Not Available\nWhen you view this situation, it\nisn't at is was last year either. At\nleast the workers don't think so.\nThere were other jobs available then\nand with pretty good rates. Now\nworkers finding re-employment often\ndo so at cuts up to 50 cents an hour.\nI had a survey made for me in up\nstate New York. In the upper Mo\nhawk valley from Little Falls to\nFrankfort there is a working force\nof a few hundred less than 13,000.\nPractically 50 per cent of them are\nunemployed today\u2014only about three\nfourths drawing unemployment in\nsurance benefits, the rest having ex\nhausted theirs. There are few pros\npects for employment. Even the\nUnited States Employment Office at\nHerkimer admitted that. Workers\nin the area have ceased moving\naround. There isn't a community in\nupstate New York which could ab\nsorb them. Many of them are re\nturning to small farms, others are\njust waiting for better times. In the\ncommunities themselves, there has\nbeen little change in prices even\nthough the businessmen are despon\ndent because clothing, appliances,\nand furniture are not maving. Last\nmonth one furniture dealer in the\nIlion-Herkimer area did a total of\n$16 business in one week. He had\nto lay off his one remaining sales\nman. All merchants have similarly\ncurtailed their sales forces since pur\nchases have been so few.\nSome of the unemployment has\nbeen due to a certain type of foreign\npolicy. The Remington-Rand Com\npany has been moving out plants to\nThose workers\nEurope and Asia,\nshow some resentment to the Foreign\nAid Program. They say American\ncapital is needed to develop back\nward areas in other parts of the\nworld; this is an area which needs\ndeveloping, why not pour some capi\ntal in here.\nUnemployment Figures\nThis illustration is not yet typical.\nbut there is considerable fear that\nsuch areas will grow. Actually, in\nthe United States today around 4,\n000,000 people are jobless, or about\none-and-a-third million more than\nthe official Census Bureau figures\nestimate. Those Census figures do\nnot include people on lay-offs up to\n30 days which may become perma\nnent, nor do they include people who\nwill take new jobs in 30 days. They\nnot report people only employed\npart-time or people on the labor\nfringe\u2014women, young people, and\nfolks who move in and out of\nlabor market as economic condi\ntions warrant.\nActually in January,\nBut of the people\nwho were employed at the 1948 la\npeak, around 4,000,000 are today\nunemployed.\n1949, there were also 12,000,000 out\n55,000,000 workers employed less\nthan 40 hours a week, and nine-and\na-half million employed less than 35\nhours.\nOnly three-fourths of our\nworkers are covered by unemploy\nment insurance, which is paid them\nfrom 14 to 26 weeks.\nRecently, Ewan Clague, commis\nsioner of Labor Statistics in the De\npartment of Labor, was reported as\nj saying there was no cause for\ncern unless the jobless rolls were to\njump to five million and stay there\nbeyond April. Actually, when there\nare five million unemployed you have\na real force for recession already\noperating.\ncon\nRecession Here For Some\nBecause of what has happened to\ntheir buying power, one-fourth of\nthe people in the United States are\nalready experiencing a recession. If\nthe present trend in lay-offs con\ntinues with its subsequent reduction\nin consumer buying and business ex\npenditure, the unemployment figure\nby the end of 1949 could well reach\nseven million with their buying pow\ner cut at least in half. We have\ndone a beautiful job of dissipating\nin record time the tremendous back\nlog of buying power of many of\nthese people, built up during the war,\nwhich was to keep us rolling for\nyears after.\nIf nothing were done by the fed\neral government to pick up a result\ning fifteen billion dollar income\nslack, then we would be in serious\ntrouble. We are still in a spotty\npicture. On one side there are lay\noffs in many fields. Yet, on the\nother side with steel, metal mining,\na large part of automobile produc\ntion and factories obtaining big gov\nernment contracts still booming and\nsalting away fat profits, no one rule\nor criterion applies everywhere. Too,\nretail prices are dropping slowly,\nsome actually going up. Therefore,\nsome workers' wage increases are\nstill justified.\nWorkers' Incomes Dropping\nLeon Keyserling of the President's\nEconomic Advisers said here in\nWashington the other day that while\nemployees in 1939 had about sixty\nsix per cent of the total national in\ncome, they had only sixty-one-and\na-half per cent last year. They are\ndropping close to the undesirable low\nfifty-eight per cent of the income\nwhich they held when the crash came\nin 1929. Business and professional\nincomes almost doubled their share\nof the national income in the last ten\nyears, however. Keyserling was very\nspecific that profits had been run\nning higher than needed to maintain\ncurrent and even somewhat increased\nlevels of business investment.\n1929 one of the main causes of the\nIn\nIs World War III\nImminent?\nThere seems to b\u00e9 an organized\neffort to keep the cold war close to\nboiling point, just short of exploding\nlike the Farben chemical works or\nWorld War I and II. .If war comes,\nno holds will be barred and the war\nwill be more barbarous than any\nhere-to-fore to combatants and civil\nians alike.\nWhile poison gas has been out\nlawed as a weapon of war, the atom\nbomb which creates the deadliest gas,\nor radiation known today, was used\nin the last war and it is openly\nboasted that it will be used again,\nOf course, it was no\nmore necessary against defeated\nJapan than it would be against any\nfuture opponent. As no nation\nwould relish to be the first to use\nit, it would simply be a matter of\nGaston and Alphonse, each one\nblaming the other for starting it.\nStrategic Bases\nU. S. has Russia surrounded on\nnecessary.\nthree sides with actual, and poten\ntial bases from which to launch air\nattacks, all the way from Greenland\nto Philippine Islands and Japan while\nRussia has no such bases anywhere\nnear Continental U. S.\nBarring the use of atom bombs,\npoison gas and bacteria, of which\nRussia may have a supply too, she\nis in a stronger geographical posi\ntion for defense than U. S. but as\neither side is practically immune\nfrom a land invasion by the other,\nthat can be ruled out as of no vital\nimportance as the decisive factors in\nthe war will be: air power first and\nsea-power second.\nRussia has an airfleet and Snorkel\nsub-fleet second to none and U. S.\nsphere-of-influence is much over ex\ntended for practical defense. Posi\ntions in China, Korea, Philippine\nJapan would likely be\nvacated instead of using the troops\nthere as expendables and the Iran\noil fields would be impossible to hold.\nIn fact, the oil fields there would be\nan easy mark for the Baku aif-fleet\nto take over or destroy. She would\nhave mainland air bases in China,\nKorea, and Vladivostok and, with the\naid of her submarines would contrbl\nthe Chamkhatka sea, the China\nand the sea of Japan and her subs\nplay havoc with our Pacific com\nmerce.\nIn case of a war-of-attrition, it\nwould be a costly struggle between\nr J. S. navy and Russia subs with pos\nsibly no decisive victory for either,\nbut our Oriental trade would be def\ninitely broken.\nand most vulnerable foreign asset,\nIranian oil would be lost, for the\ntime being, at least.\nU. S. Navy would be practically\nin full control of all the\ncept the Arctic which would be most\nly in Russia's hands, at least from\nPetsame to Bering Strait.\nCould Russia Be Isolated\nHer northern-sea-route could be\ncut in Bering Strait from the Alaska\nside but she only uses that part little\nmore than three months in a year\non account of ice. The Baltic traf\nfic could be blocked in the ,North\nSea, leaving her but two exits to\nher ocean trade. This would, no\ndoubt, hurt her to some extent, but\nwould not seriously effect her in\nternal economy as she is more self\n35\nas\nto\nsea\nOur most valuable\noceans, ex\nsufficient in raw material than any\nother country, United States in\ncluded.\neconomy,\npotential enemy, it would be\nOn the other hand, the disruption\nof commerce between U. S. and Eur\nope and the Far East could have a\ndisastrous effect on our internal\nIf we had no actual, or\nneces\ndepression was that too few people\nwere getting too great a share of the\nnational income,\nnot keep up with production because\nthey didn't have an adequate share\nof the income. And that tendency\nis developing again.\nThese are factors in our troubles;\nHigh taxes needed to maintain a siz\nable non-productive part-time war\neconomy; unreasonable profits of big\nindustries; industry prices in many\nfields again tending to pull\nfrom farm prices; and constantly re\nducing take-home pay of workers.\nWe have overcome most of our war\ntime shortages, too.\ntroubles ahead unless the government\nbegins to think of and prepare for\nthe future. To wait until we have\nfive or six million unemployed will\nbe too late.\nConsumers could\naway\nThis means\nPEACE\nIS THIS THE ANSWER?\nmm\n\nm\ni\nW\u00ea\nmmtsa\nV i\nr V;\n\n\u25a0tfi\nI'\nh\n\u2022Mi\nv\n\nr\n\nlUS.\nm\n\nt\n'\u25a0n\n\nmm\ny\n-i\nWm\nV\n\n\n1\n.'iiS\n1/\n\n_\nr\ny\n\n\u2022J.\nf\u00c2\nK\n'v\nV\nk\nm\nAL PTTUJiU.\nmt\nV\nbringing\ninto a twenty-year alliance with west-j\nern European countries against Rus\nsia and her neighbors. The North\nAtlantic Pact will virtually commit\nAmericans, if the Senate ratifies, to\nmuster, equip and maintain millions\nof men and provide thouasnds of\nairplanes and mechanized equipment\nto fight World War III. Reasons\ngiven for this unprecedented action\non the part of the US is to enforce\nEuropean economic recovery and re\ntard the alleged expansionist aims of\nRussia.\nMilitary strategists look to France\nas the immediate battleground if\ncomes.\nwill be the final battleground.\nOwen. Lattimore, writing in THE\nGAZETTE AND DAIL\") ,says: \"The\nall-important question will be wheth\nthe United States Senate ratifies\nthe document (North Atlantic Pact)\nso carefully, delicately and secretly\nwar\nAll realists know the world\ner\nsary to create one in order to jus\ntify the heavy taxation and the gran\ndiose scheme of defense, or rather\noffense, now contemplated. A. E.\nANDERSON, Butte.\nMINE-MILL WINS TRAVEL\nPAY FOR MEMBERSHIP\nIN NEVADA\nA smashing victory for every und\nerground and open pit miner in the\nstate of Nevada was won by Mine\nMill recently with complete passage\nof a brand new \"collar-to-collar\" pay\nlaw by the Nevada legislature and its\nsignature by Governor Pittman.\nLnder the new law travel time\nPay\u2014so bitterly opposed by all min\ning companies\u2014must now be paid\nfor all hours \"consumed from the\ntime of entering the collar of the\nshaft or portal or consumed in\nleaving the surface of any tunnel,\nopen cut or open pit works, for the\nplace of work therein, and returning\nthereto from said place or point of\nwork.\"\nWith the passage of the Nevada\ntravel time law, hundreds of Mine\nMill members throughout the state\nwill benefit by collecting pay for the\nmany hours of work the companies\nhave been getting scot free.\nOLEOMARGARINE\nRemoval of all taxes on oleomar\ngarine has been advocated by the\nhouse agricultural committee,\n24-3 vote.\nThe committee, in approving H. R.\n2023, also gave the nod to\npresent license fees charged to\nufacturers, distributors and retailers\nof oleo.\non a\nremoving\nman\nj negotiated by the State department.\"\nFreda Kirchway in THE NATION\nsays: \"The Atlantic Pact is tangled\nj in knots of strictly American manu\ni facture. Nothing could have been\nj more amateurish than the diplomacy\napplied to the pact negotiations. Ob\nviously we held the whip hand.\"\n1 Recently 460 bishops, preachers,\nmissionaries and other delegates to\nthe National Study Conference on\nthe Churches and World Order in\nthe Hotel Cleveland, according to\nTIME MAGAZINE, asked the U.S.\nSenate to postpone final action on\nthe Atlantic Pact until the nation\nhas had opportunity to full discus\nsion of all provisions and implica\ntions.\nJames Patton of the National\nFarmers Union has asked for a great\nnational debate on American foreign\npolicy so that the people will know\nwhat is going on.\n\u2014From Montana F. U. News.\nFACTS, FIGURES..\nWHO BENEFITS FROM\nINCREASED PRODUCTIVITY?\nBetween 1939 and 1948, overall\nproductivity has increased almost\none-third.\nThis means that thre workers now\nare doing the work that four turned\nout in 1939.\nIn the electrical equipment indus\ntry, the increase in productivity dur\ning the same period was even greater\n\u201439%.\nThe corporations have not lowered\nprices in response to the increased\nproductivity.\nLeon Keyserling of the President's\nCouncil of Economic Advisers said:\n\"The leveling off or softening of\nsome prices has been exaggerated or\nmisinterpreted.\"\nHe noted continued price increases\non rents, fuels and house furnishings\nand metal products. He also pre\ndicted a seasonal rise in the price of\nmeats in the spring and summer.\nWith prices high, working people\nhave not the purchasing power to\nabsorb the increased production,\na result, in December 1948, 700,000\nworkers were thrown out of work\nand the number of workers on part\ntime increased one half million,\nthe electrical industry alone, 80,000\nworkers lost their jobs.\n(Sources\nAs\nIn\nOver-all productivity\ncomputed from the Economic Report\nof the President, January, 1949;\nelectrical industry productivity fr\nElectrical World. January 29,' _\nunemployment from Census Bur\nrelease.\nom\n1949;\neau\nDEMAND THE UNION LABEL","height":"20139","width":"13992"}}
